cleaned_message: The Right to Notify We Saxons live in a state in the US where the homeschool laws are very relaxed. Each year, we are required to do two things in order to be in compliance with the law: (1) we must either have an assessor assess our childrens progress, or we must have our children take a test; and (2) we must notify our countys superintendent of schools of our intention to notify. I have a pool of homeschool-friendly assessors I choose from, and I make sure that they are aware of the minimal homeschooling laws governing us. I give them the absolute minimal amount of information needed to assess that our children have made progress, give them shekels and get my minimally informative paper that I will submit at a later point to my state. The paper simply states that the assessment has been completed, and that the childs progress for the year has been in accordance with the childs abilities. I opt for the minimally invasive and minimally informative procedures because I want the state to know as little as possible. This assessment is not to satisfy our desire for information on our childs academic progress; it is merely to be compliant with the letter of the law (and to provide no more information than legally required). In the first week of August all homeschooling parents who know their game will submit their paperwork to the state at the same time, in an effort to bombard the states authorities with our notifications of intent to homeschool. You see: in our state there is only a short time period after receiving your letter during which the authorities are allowed to ask for more information. After that, they have no legal footing to ask for information, as long as you can prove when the authorities received your letter of intent and the previously mentioned assessment. Were required to submit our notification within a few weeks of the start of the school year, but our states national homeschool support group advises all of its members to submit those NOIs in the first week of August, en masse. It is every seasoned homeschoolers hope that the superintendent will be rather overwhelmed by the many notification letters he or she will get, and will not be duly motivated to start asking questions they ought not to be asking anyway. Since public schools are gearing up to resume their indoctrination camps soon, it is a good idea to hop over to www.hslda.org and to ensure that you are in compliance with the law. If you are fearful of your own ability to follow the letter of the law, become a member of the HSLDA so you can count on their legal advice. Its August, friends. Time to get compliant with the law and to continue to homeschool the children. -Mrs. Saxon @Dissidenthomeschool

Mr. Bond writes from Austrian prison, where he's been sentenced to 10 years for writing 'hateful' songs: July 22, 2022 Hello Friends, If you're reading this, you are probably aware of my arrest in January 2021 and my trial in March 2022, and the insane verdict I received. Thank you to everyone who contributed to my legal fund, thank you to all the guys who organized the whole thing and even put up a website to help me. I'm totally cut off in here, so for a long time, I had no idea about all the things that were going on outside. I'd love to get to know the people behind all those nice and encouraging messages and link up with you, especially the closer ones from Austria and Germany...but of course I understand you wish to remain in the dark.
